:'''V.''' The repugnance of the Latin language to the Greek combined vowels Œ±Œø has caused the translocation of them in ''Alumento'' for ŒõŒ±ŒøŒºŒ≠Œ¥œâŒΩ (Paul. ex Fest. p. 18 M&uuml;ll.).&mdash;Greek &alpha; is suppressed in ''Hercules'' from `ŒóœÅŒ±Œ∫ŒªŒ∑œÇ (probably in consequence of the inserted ''u;'' in late Latin we find ''Heracla'' and ''Heracula,'' cf. Ritschl, in Rhein. Mus. Neue Folge, vol. 12, p. 108).
:'''VI.''' Latin ''ƒÉ'' was early combined with the vowels ''i'' and ''u'', forming the diphthongs ''ai'' and ''au;'' by changing the ''i'' into ''e'', the diphthong ''ai'' soon became ''ae''. So we find in the oldest inscriptions: <small>AIDE, AIDILIS, AIQVOM, GNAIVOD, HAICE, DVELONAI, TABELAI, DATAI,</small> etc., which soon gave place to aedem, aedilis, aequom, Gnaeo, haec, Bellonae, tabellae, datae, etc. (the Col. Rostr. has <small>PRAESENTE, PRAEDAD,</small> and the S. C. de Bacch. <small>AEDEM.</small> The triphthong ''aei'', found in <small>CONQVAEISIVEI</small>(?), is very rare; Miliar. Popil. lin. 11, v. Ritschl, l. 1. p. 21). In some poets the old genetive singular of the first declension (''-ai'') is preserved, but is dissyllabic, ''&acirc;&icirc;''. So in Ennius: ''Alb&acirc;&icirc; Long&acirc;&icirc;, terr&acirc;&icirc; frugifer&acirc;&icirc;, frondos&acirc;&icirc;, lun&acirc;&icirc;, vi&acirc;&icirc;;'' in Vergil: ''aul&acirc;&icirc;, aur&acirc;&icirc;, aqu&acirc;&icirc;, pict&acirc;&icirc;;'' in Ausonius: ''her&acirc;&icirc;.''
:'''B.''' ''ae'' as well as ''au'' are changed into other vowels.
:'''1.''' The sound of ''ae, e,'' and ''oe'' being very similar, these vowels are often interchanged in the best manuscripts. So we find ''caerimonia'' and ''cerimonia, caepa'' and ''c&ecirc;pa, saeculum'' and ''s&ecirc;culum; scaena'' and ''sc&ecirc;na; caelum'' and ''coelum, haedus'' and ''hoedus, maestus'' and ''moestus; cena, coena,'' and ''caena,'' etc.
:'''2.''' In composition and reduplications ''ae'' becomes ''&icirc;:'' aequus, ''in&icirc;quus;'' quaero, ''inqu&icirc;ro;'' laedo, ''ill&icirc;do;'' taedet, ''pert&icirc;sum'' (noticed by Cicero); aestumo, ''ex&icirc;stumo;'' caedo, ''cec&icirc;di, conc&icirc;do, homic&icirc;da.''
:'''3.''' ''ae'' is also changed into ''&icirc;'' in a Latinized word of Greek origin: `ŒëœáŒ±ŒπœåœÇ (`ŒëœáŒ±Œπ''F''œåœÇ), ''Ach&icirc;vus.''
:'''4.''' The diphthong ''au'' is often changed to ''&ocirc;'' and ''&ucirc;'' (the latter particularly in compounds): ''caudex, c&ocirc;dex; Claudius, Clodius; lautus, l&ocirc;tus; plaustrum, pl&ocirc;strum; plaudo, pl&ocirc;do, expl&ocirc;do; paululum, p&ocirc;lulum; faux, suff&ocirc;co; si audes'' (according to Cicero or according to others, si audies), ''s&ocirc;des'', etc.; ''claudo, incl&ucirc;do; causa, acc&ucirc;so.'' Hence in some words a regular gradation of ''au, o, u'' is found: ''claudo, cl&ocirc;dicare, cl&ucirc;do; raudus, r&ocirc;dus, r&ucirc;dus; caupo, c&ocirc;pa, c&ucirc;pa; naugae, n&ocirc;gae'' (both forms in the manuscripts of Plautus), ''n&ucirc;gae; fraustra, frode, frude'' (in manuscripts of Vergil); cf. Ritschl, in Wintercatalog 1854-55, and O. Ribbeck, in Jahn's Neue Jahrb. vol. 77, p. 181 sq.&mdash;The change of ''au'' into ''oe'' and ''e'' appears only in audio, (oboedio) ''ob&ecirc;dio.''
:'''5.''' ''Au'' sometimes takes the place of ''av-: faveo, fautum, favitor, fautor; navis, navita, nauta;'' avis, ''auceps, auspex.'' So Latin ''aut'' corresponds to Sanscrit ''ave'' (whence ''-v&acirc;'', Latin ''-ve''), Osc. ''avti,'' Umbr. ''ute, ote;'' and so the Latin preposition ''ab,'' through ''av,'' becomes ''au'' in the words ''aufero'' and ''aufugio'' (prop. av-fero, av-fugio, for ab-fero, ab-fugio). Vide the article ab ''init''.
:'''VII.''' In primitive roots, which have their kindred forms in the sister-languages of the Latin, the original ''a'', still found in the Sanscrit, is in Latin either preserved or more frequently changed into other vowels.
:'''A.''' ''Original a'' preserved: Sanscrit ''m&acirc;tri'', Latin m&acirc;ter; Sanscrit ''bhr&acirc;tri'', Latin fr&acirc;ter; Sanscrit ''n&acirc;s&acirc;,'' Latin n&acirc;sus and n&acirc;ris; Sanscrit ''ap'', Latin aqua; Sanscrit ''apa,'' Latin ab; Sanscrit ''n&acirc;ma,'' Latin nƒÉm; Sanscrit ''catur'', Latin, quattuor (in Greek changed: œÑŒ≠œÑœÑŒ±œÅŒµœÇ); Sanscrit ''cap&ucirc;la'', Latin cƒÉput (in Greek changed: Œ∫ŒµœÜŒ±ŒªŒÆ, etc.).
:'''B.''' ''Original a'' is changed into other Latin vowels&mdash;
:'''1.''' Into ''e'': Sanscrit ''ad'', Latin ed (ƒïdo); Sanscrit ''as'', Latin es (esse); Sanscrit ''pat'', Latin pet (peto); Sanscrit ''p&acirc;d,'' Latin pƒïd (p&ecirc;s); Sanscrit ''dant'', Latin dent (dens); Sanscrit ''gan,'' Latin gen (gigno); Sanscrit ''m&acirc;'', Latin m&ecirc;-tior; Sanscrit ''saptan'', Latin septem; Sanscrit ''da≈õan'', Latin decem; Sanscrit ''≈õata'', Latin centum; Sanscrit ''aham'', Latin ƒïgo; Sanscrit ''p&acirc;ra'', Latin per; Sanscrit ''pa≈õu'', Latin pƒïcus; Sanscrit asva'', Latin ƒïquus, etc.
:'''2.''' Into ''i'': Sanscrit ''an-'', ''a-'' (neg. part.), Latin in-; Sanscrit ''ana'' (prep.), Latin in; Sanscrit ''antar'', Latin inter; Sanscrit ''abhara'', Latin imber; Sanscrit ''panca'', Latin quinque, etc.
:'''3.''' Into ''o'': Sanscrit ''avi'', Latin ≈èvi (ovis); Sanscrit ''vac'', Latin v≈èc (voco); Sanscrit ''pra,'' Latin pro; Sanscrit ''p&acirc;'', Latin po (p&ocirc;tum); Sanscrit ''n&acirc;ma'', Latin n&ocirc;men; Sanscrit ''api,'' Latin ≈èb; Sanscrit ''navan'', Latin n≈èvem; Sanscrit ''nava'', Latin n≈èvus, etc.
:'''4.''' Into ''u'': Sanscrit ''marmara,'' Latin murmur.
:'''5.''' Into ''ai, ae:'' Sanscrit ''prati'', Latin (prai) prae; Sanscrit ''≈õa≈õpa,'' Latin caespes.
:'''6.''' Into ''different vowels'' in the different derivatives: Sanscrit ''m&acirc;'', Latin m&ecirc;-tior, m≈èdus; Sanscrit ''prac'', Latin prƒïcor, pr≈ècus; Sanscrit ''vah'', Latin vƒïho, via.
:'''C.''' Sometimes the Latin has preserved the original ''a'', while even the Sanscrit has changed it: Latin pa-, pater, Sanscrit. ''p&acirc;'', ''pitri.''
:'''2.''' As an abbreviation A. usually denotes the praenomen ''Aulus;'' A. A.=''Auli duo'', Inscriptiones Orelli 1530 (but A.A.=Aquae Aponi, ''the modern Abano'', ibidem 1643 sequens; 2620; 3011). The three directors of the mint were designated by <small>III. VIRI A. A. A. F. F.</small> (i. e. auro, argento, aeri flando, feriundo), ibidem 569; 2242; 2379; 3134 alia; so also A. A. A., ibidem 3441 (compare Cicero's Epistulae ad Familiares 7, 13 ''at the end'', and see the article [[Triumviri]]); A. D. A. ''agris dandis adsignandis,'' and A. I. A. ''agris judicandis adsignandis;'' A. O. ''amico optimo;'' A. P. ''a populo''  or ''aediliciae potestatis;'' A. P. R.  ''aerario populi Romani.''&mdash;Upon the voting tablets in judicial trials A. denotes ''absolvo''; hence A. is called ''littera salutaris,'' Cicero's Miles Gloriosus 6, 15; vide [[littera]]. In the Roman Comitia A. (=''antiquo'') denoted the rejection of the point in question; see [[antiquo]]. In Cicero's Tusculan Disputations (Tusculanae Disputationes) the A. designated one of the disputants=''adulescens'' or ''auditor'', opposed to M. for ''magister'' or ''Marcus'' (Cicero); but it is to be remarked that the letters A and M do not occur in the best manuscripts of this treatise; refer to the editions ad Cicero's Tusculanae Disputationes 1, 5, 9.&mdash;In dates A. D.=''ante diem;'' vide [[ante]]; A. U. C.=''anno urbis conditae;'' A. P. R. C. ''anno post Romam conditam.''
:'''3.a.''' ''preposition''=ab, see [[ab]].
:'''4.ƒÅ.''' ''interjection''=ah, see [[ah]].

